Kronecker PCA

Can Hakan Dagidir

2022-05-19

Data:

  • 6 months training 2019 Jan to Jun
  • 6 months test 2020 Jan to Jun
  • 5 of the datasets have 3x3 locations, the other one (aliaga) has 2x2 locations

Kronecker PCA in Depth Analysis

Figure 1

Here we see the change in train and test errors as we change the number of principal components in Kronecker PCA.

The numbers on the plot represent the number of PCs at the lowest test error.

Figure 2

Here we see the change in explained variance with number of principal components.

Blue and Purple lines represent 99%th and 99.9%th explained varience.

Comments of Figure 1 and 2:

  • We see no improvement in test results after using 6 principal components.

  • Even 1 principal component explains more than 90% of the variance and with 5-6 PCs we were able to capture almost all of the variance.

  • Training Performance is also similar, which is good.

Conclusion

  • Kronecker’s explained variance and train/test errors look nice.
  • Explained Variance is very high in the first PCs. (compare this to PCA and Kernel PCA)
